record.text:
I asked @asrivkin.bsky.social "Any asteroids named for the Beatles?"
üî≠
Alert grade-school comedians:

1. Answer is 4147 Lennon, 4148 McCartney, 4149 Harrison. And 4150 is unique, because it's the only asteroid that is also a Starr.

2. They may be named for Beatles, but they are also Rolling Stones.

value.text: Following up--they're numbers 4147-4150, named Lennon, McCartney, Harrison, and Starr. They're all medium-albedo, between 5-10 km diameter (George's is largest, John's is smallest), and in the inner half of the belt (George's is in the middle belt for those who divide it into three sections).

embed.alt:
A video of about half a second just before second contact at the April 8, 2024 total solar eclipse. The Moon is a dark disk sliding in front of the Sun, which is mostly detectable as a white haze against which the Moon is silhoutted. In the upper left quadrant of the overlapping disks, there are numerous pink prominences appearing to extend out from the Moon's edge.

At about 10 o'clock the last bits of the brilliant disk of the Sun are shining through lunar valleys so that, as the video progresses, what was an arc of overexposed white dwindles down to just a few very bright beads (Baily's Beads).

record.text: I tried to post this as a gif several weeks ago and it failed. Trying again as a video. I practiced and practiced automated imaging for the April 8 TSE and then made a change in the field just before. Computer crashed 10s after 2nd contact. Alas. This is the last 0.5s before. üî≠ #astrophotography

images.alt: "NGC 3184, a delicate face-on spiral galaxy in the constellation Ursa Major, graces this image with a soft swirl of cosmic dust and bright, young star clusters. Set against a dark backdrop of distant stars, the galaxy's spiral arms gently wind around a luminous core. The foreground is dotted with a handful of bright stars, their bold colors and rays adding contrast and depth to this stellar composition. Known as the "Little Pinwheel Galaxy," NGC 3184 lies approximately 40 million light-years away, making it a prominent but distant gem in the vast cosmic tapestry." #space #astrophotography
